# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2017-swiss-referendums
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Helvetic Republic over several months in 1798.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Modelled after the French Constitution of the Year III of 1795, the new constitution was approved by voters.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] In some places voting took places in public assemblies, whilst in others the local councils took the decision.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Helvetic Republic on 25 May 1802.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Unlike the constitution approved in 1798, the new constitution, known as the Malmaison constitution, did not provide for any referendums.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Non-voters were assumed to have voted in favour of the new constitution, a measure put in place to prevent its rejection.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] As a result, 72.17% of voters were deemed to be in favour.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in Switzerland in July and August 1848, the first referendum on record in the Swiss Confederation.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] The new constitution was approved by 72.8% of voters and a majority of cantons.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] In order to pass, any amendments to the constitution needed a double majority; a majority of the popular vote and majority of the cantons.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] The decision of each canton was based on the vote in that canton.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] Full cantons counted as one vote, whilst half cantons counted as half.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland between 1 and 27 October 1848.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left emerged as the largest group, winning 79 of the 111 seats in the National Council.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] The 111 members of the National Council were elected from 52 single- and multi-member constituencies.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] In six cantons (Appenzell Innerrhoden, Appenzell Ausserrhoden, Glarus, Nidwalden, Obwalden and Uri), National Council members were elected by the Landsgemeinde.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 26 October 1851.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left remained the largest group in the National Council, winning 78 of the 120 seats.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The elections were held under the Federal law concerning the elections to the National Council, which had been passed on 21 December 1850.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The 120 members of the National Council were elected in 49 single- and multi-member constituencies; there was one seat for every 20,000 citizens, with seats allocated to cantons in proportion to their population.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The 1850 law reduced the number of constituencies from 52, but increased the number of seats from 111; Aargau, Glarus, Lucerne, Neuchâtel, Vaud and Zürich gained one seat each, whilst Bern gained three seats.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The law also set the election date as the last Sunday in October and introduced a three-year term.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The elections were held using a three-round system; candidates had to receive a majority in the first or second round to be elected; if it went to a third round, only a plurality was required.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] Voters could cast as many votes as there were seats in their constituency.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1854-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 29 October 1854.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1854-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left remained the largest group in the National Council, winning 80 of the 120 seats.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1857-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 28 October 1857.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/1857-swiss-federal-election] Compulsory voting was introduced in the Canton of Schaffhausen for the elections, with the canton seeing the highest turnout at 86.4% compared to the 46.5% figure nationally.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/2017-swiss-referendums] Seven national referendums were held in Switzerland during 2017.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/2017-swiss-referendums] Polling took place on 12 February, 21 May and 24 September, whilst no referendum was scheduled for the November date.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/2017-swiss-referendums] One referendum was held on 21 May on whether to accept the new Energy Act, establishing the Energy Strategy 2050, which seeks to phase out nuclear energy and increase renewable energy and energy efficiency.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/2017-swiss-referendums] The plan was opposed by the Swiss People's Party, which launched the optional referendum against it.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/2017-swiss-referendums] The Energy Act was approved by 58% of voters.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/2017-swiss-referendums] The latter two referendums were related, and the Federal Act on the 2020 Pension Reforms would only have gone into effect if the proposed VAT increase was also accepted by voters.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/2017-swiss-referendums] The pension reform would have raised the women's retirement age to 65.
[src:2017-swiss-referendums/2017-swiss-referendums] The proposed reforms were supported by centre and left-of-centre parties and opposed by right-of-centre parties such as the FDP.The Liberals and the Swiss People's Party.
